data.title: Traces of Evil
data.meta_description: Remaining Nazi sites then and now
data.text:
Party members in civilian clothing blocked the entrances to Jewish-owned shops and department stores in Frankfurt am Main, and shouted insults at customers, beating up those who persisted in trying to go in. They smashed the shop windows, and when police arrived to arrest them, they became so threatening that the officers had to draw their weapons. This campaign proved the prelude to a much wider wave of economic terror, in which local Party organisations threatened to withdraw welfare payments from anyone seen entering a Jewish-owned shop. Civil servants and municipal employees in many localities were ordered to stay clear of such establishments.

This would culminate from October 1941 to March 1945 with the deportations of Jews from Frankfurt and the surrounding area. Between October 1941 and September 1942, the Gestapo rented the basement of the Grossmarkthalle for 24 hours before the deportations. Here the , Gestapo officials, municipal welfare workers and officials from the tax office took away their last valuables, money, ID cards, ration cards and their apartment keys befoe forcing them onto the waiting trains and taken to various ghettos, concentration camps, extermination camps, and other places of execution.
